    .entry-details
      %p.desc
        %strong> Description:
        Get the value of a style property for the first element in the set of matched elements.
      %ul.signatures
        %li#css-propertyName.signature
          %h4.name
            %span.versionAdded>
              version added:
              %a{:href => "/category/version/1.0/"} 1.0
            \.css( propertyName )
          %p.arguement
            %strong> propertyName
            A CSS property.
      .longdesc
        %p
          The
          %code .css()
          method is a convenient way to get a style property from the first matched element, especially in light of the different ways browsers access most of those properties (the
          %code getComputedStyle()
          method in standards-based browsers versus the
          %code currentStyle
          and
          %code runtimeStyle
          properties in Internet Explorer) and the different terms browsers use for certain properties. For example, Internet Explorer's DOM implementation refers to the
          %code float
          property as
          = succeed "," do
            %code styleFloat
          while W3C standards-compliant browsers refer to it as
          = succeed "." do
            %code cssFloat
          The
          %code .css()
          method accounts for such differences, producing the same result no matter which term we use. For example, an element that is floated left will return the string
          %code left
          for each of the following three lines:
        %ol
          %li
            %code $('div.left').css('float');
          %li
            %code $('div.left').css('cssFloat');
          %li
            %code $('div.left').css('styleFloat');
        %p
          Also, jQuery can equally interpret the CSS and DOM formatting of multiple-word properties. For example, jQuery understands and returns the correct value for both
          %code .css('background-color')
          and
          = succeed "." do
            %code .css('backgroundColor')
        %p
          Shorthand CSS properties (e.g. margin, background, border) are not supported. For example, if you want to retrieve the rendered margin, use:
          %code $(elem).css('marginTop')
          and
          = succeed "," do
            %code $(elem).css('marginRight')
          and so on.
      %h3 Example:
      #entry-examples.entry-examples
        #example-0
          %h4
            %span.desc To access the background color of a clicked div.
          %pre
            %code.example.demo-code
              :preserve
                &lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
                &lt;html&gt;
                &lt;head&gt;
                  &lt;style&gt;
                div { width:60px; height:60px; margin:5px; float:left; }
                  &lt;/style&gt;
                  &lt;script src="http://code.jquery.com/jquery-latest.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
                &lt;/head&gt;
                &lt;body&gt;
                	
                &lt;span id="result"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;
                &lt;div style="background-color:blue;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
                &lt;div style="background-color:rgb(15,99,30);"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
                
                &lt;div style="background-color:#123456;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
                &lt;div style="background-color:#f11;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
                &lt;script&gt;
                $("div").click(function () {
                  var color = $(this).css("background-color");
                  $("#result").html("That div is &lt;span style='color:" +
                                     color + ";'&gt;" + color + "&lt;/span&gt;.");
                });
                
                &lt;/script&gt;
                &lt;/body&gt;
                &lt;/html&gt;          %h4 Demo:
          .demo.code-demo
